# DB Layer — Row Mapping Conventions

The backend uses two distinct shapes for todo data. **Never mix them.**

| Type | Where used | Naming | Example |
|------|-----------|--------|---------|
| `TodoRow` | Knex query results, DB writes | `snake_case` | `created_at`, `is_completed` |
| `Todo` | Service return values, API responses | `camelCase` | `createdAt`, `isCompleted` |

## Mapping Pattern

Conversion must happen **inside the service layer**, not in controllers or routes.

```typescript
// src/services/todoService.ts

// ❌ BAD — returning raw DB row to the controller
return db('todos').where({ id }).first(); // TodoRow leaks out

// ✅ GOOD — map in the service
function toTodo(row: TodoRow): Todo {
  return {
    id: row.id,
    title: row.title,
    completed: row.is_completed,
    createdAt: row.created_at,
  };
}

async getTodoById(id: number): Promise<Todo> {
  const row = await db<TodoRow>('todos').where({ id }).first();
  if (!row) { /* throw 404 error */ }
  return toTodo(row);
}
```

## Migration Conventions

- File name: `YYYYMMDDHHMMSS_<verb>_<table>.ts` (e.g. `20260329120000_create_todos.ts`).
- Always include both `up` and `down` exports.
- Column names in migrations must be `snake_case`.
- Run migrations via `npm run migrate` — never edit applied migration files.

## Rules

- `TodoRow` is defined in `src/types/todo.ts` — import from there, never re-declare inline.
- Controllers must only ever receive and return the `Todo` domain type.
- Do not use `knex.raw()` unless absolutely necessary; prefer the query builder.
- Add `timestamps()` (creates `created_at` / `updated_at`) to every new table migration.
